About Matplotlib¶

What is matplotlib?¶

Matplotlib, short for matix plotting library is a comprehensive library for creating static, animated, and interactive visualizations in Python.

Source: https://matplotlib.org/

Import Matplotlib with import command¶

Matplotlib is officially aliased as mpl.

In [2]:
import matplotlib as mpl

If Matplotlib is not installed, we will encounter a ModuleNotFoundError¶

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'matplotlib'

Use pip install at Terminal to install matplotlib¶

pip install matplotlib

Check version and its installation file path¶

  • __version__ attribute
  • __file__ attribute
In [3]:
print(mpl.__version__)
print(mpl.__file__)

3.3.2
/opt/conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/matplotlib/__init__.py

We will use matplotlib.pyplot through this chapter, which is a plotting module in matplotlib, officially aliased as plt¶

In [4]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

Why matplotlib?¶

Visualization plays a vital role among exploratory data analysis. Sometimes it is extremly difficult for human to understand raw data, functions, or formulas.

The abstractness of raw data¶

In [5]:
arr = np.random.normal(size=10000)
arr
Out[5]:
array([ 0.46552347,  1.09230233, -1.45207542, ..., -0.90509376,
       -0.01143045, -0.11561234])

The abstractness of functions¶

Considering 2 functions below:

\begin{equation} f(p) = -log(p) \\ f(p) = -log(1-p) \end{equation}

The abstractness of formulas¶

\begin{equation} f(x) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}} \end{equation}

The concreteness of visualization for raw data¶

In [6]:
fig = plt.figure()
ax = plt.axes()
ax.hist(arr, bins=50)
plt.show()

The concreteness of visualization for functions¶

In [7]:
eps = 1e-06 # epsilon, a tiny number to avoid infinity
p = np.linspace(0 + eps, 1 - eps, 10000)
log_loss_0 = -np.log(1-p)
log_loss_1 = -np.log(p)
In [8]:
fig = plt.figure()
ax = plt.axes()
ax.plot(p, log_loss_0, label='$y_{true}=0$')
ax.plot(p, log_loss_1, label='$y_{true}=1$')
ax.legend()
plt.show()

The concreteness of visualization for formulas¶

In [9]:
x = np.linspace(-10, 10, 100)
fx = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-x))
fig = plt.figure()
ax = plt.axes()
ax.plot(x, fx)
plt.show()

The classic visualizations of all time¶

  • Charles Minard's map of Napoleon's disastrous Russian campaign of 1812.
  • Hans Rosling's 200 Countries, 200 Years, 4 Minutes.

Characteristics of a good visualization¶

  • Informative
  • Simple
  • Pretty

Two ways to plot¶

The most challenging part for matplotlib newbies is its various plotting syntaxes¶

There are 2 plotting syntaxes to adapt¶

  • Matlab style.
  • Object-oriented style.

Plotting with matlab style: stateful interface¶

In [10]:
x = np.linspace(0, np.pi*4, 100)
plt.figure()
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))
plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
plt.plot(x, np.cos(x))
plt.show()

Plotting with object-oriented style: object method interface¶

In [11]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 1)
axes[0].plot(x, np.sin(x))
axes[1].plot(x, np.cos(x))
plt.show()

We will adapt the object-oriented style.¶

The general steps¶

The general steps to create plots are:¶

  1. Creating arrays.
  2. Generating figure and axes objects(respectively or simultaneously).
  3. Calling various methods of axes object to generate main plot.
  4. Calling various methods of axes object to add elements.
  5. Show or save plots.

Creating arrays¶

In [12]:
x = np.linspace(0, np.pi*4, 100)
y = np.sin(x)

Generating figure and axes objects respectively¶

In [13]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()

Generating figure and axes objects simultaneously¶

In [14]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots()

Calling various methods of axes object to generate main plot¶

In [15]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.plot(x, y)
Out[15]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7f27d82873a0>]

Calling various methods of axes object to add elements¶

In [16]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.plot(x, y)
axes.set_title('A simple plot')
axes.set_xlabel('x')
Out[16]:
Text(0.5, 0, 'x')

Show plots¶

In [17]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.plot(x, y)
axes.set_title('A simple plot')
axes.set_xlabel('x')
plt.show()

Different methods for different plot types¶

  • scatter for scatter plots.
  • hist for histograms.
  • plot for lines.
  • bar for bar plots.
  • imshow for showing images in ndarray format.
  • ...etc.

scatter for scatter plots¶

In [20]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.scatter(x, y)
plt.show()

hist for histograms¶

In [21]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.hist(arr, bins=50)
plt.show()

plot for lines¶

In [22]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.plot(x, y)
plt.show()

bar for bar plots¶

In [23]:
outside_one_std = np.sum((arr > 1) | (arr < -1)) / arr.size
within_one_std = np.sum((-1 <= arr) & (arr <= 1)) / arr.size
y = [outside_one_std, within_one_std]
x = [1, 2]
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.bar(x, y)
plt.show()

Techniques for adding elements¶

How to add title and axis labels¶

  • set_title to add title.
  • set_xlabel to add x-axis label.
  • set_ylabel to add y-axis label.
In [26]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.imshow(arr)
axes.set_title('A very cute Schnauzer.')
axes.set_xlabel('x axis')
axes.set_ylabel('y axis')
plt.show()

How to adjust axis ticks¶

  • set_xticks to adjust x-axis ticks.
  • set_yticks to adjust y-axis ticks.
In [27]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.imshow(arr)
axes.set_title('A very cute Schnauzer.')
axes.set_xticks([])
axes.set_yticks([])
plt.show()

How to adjust axis tick labels¶

  • set_xticklabels to adjust x-axis tick labels.
  • set_yticklabels to adjust y-axis tick labels.
In [28]:
arr = np.random.normal(size=10000)
outside_one_std = np.sum((arr > 1) | (arr < -1)) / arr.size
within_one_std = np.sum((-1 <= arr) & (arr <= 1)) / arr.size
y = [outside_one_std, within_one_std]
x = [1, 2]
In [29]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.bar(x, y)
axes.set_xticks([1, 2])
axes.set_yticks([0.32,  0.68])
axes.set_xticklabels(['Outside 1 SD', 'Within 1 SD'])
axes.set_yticklabels(['32%', '68%'])
plt.show()

How to adjust axis limits¶

  • set_xlim to adjust the upper/lower limits of x-axis.
  • set_ylim to adjust the upper/lower limits of y-axis.
In [30]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.bar(x, y)
axes.set_xticks([1, 2])
axes.set_yticks([0.32,  0.68, 1])
axes.set_xticklabels(['Outside 1 SD', 'Within 1 SD'])
axes.set_yticklabels(['32%', '68%', '100%'])
axes.set_ylim([0, 1])
plt.show()

How to add texts¶

text(x, y, 'Some Strings') to add 'Some Strings' at (x, y).

In [31]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.bar(x, y)
axes.set_xticks([1, 2])
axes.set_yticks([0.32,  0.68, 1])
axes.set_xticklabels(['Outside 1 SD', 'Within 1 SD'])
axes.set_yticklabels(['32%', '68%', '100%'])
axes.set_ylim([0, 1])
axes.text(1 - 0.05, 0.35, '32%')
axes.text(2 - 0.05, 0.70, '68%')
plt.show()

How to add legends¶

lenged() and label parameterto add a legend to indicate categories.

In [32]:
x = np.linspace(0, np.pi*4, 100)
y_sin = np.sin(x)
y_cos = np.cos(x)
In [33]:
fig = plt.figure()
axes = plt.axes()
axes.plot(x, y_sin, label='sin(x)')
axes.plot(x, y_cos, label='cos(x)')
axes.legend()
plt.show()

How to create a subplot grid?¶

  • subplots(m, n) to create a ndarray with a shape (m, n).
  • There are (m, n) axes objects inside the ndarray.
  • Access axes objects through [m, n].
In [34]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3)
print(type(axes))
print(axes.shape)

<class 'numpy.ndarray'>
(2, 3)
In [35]:
x = np.linspace(0, 4*np.pi, 100)
y_sin = np.sin(x)
y_cos = np.cos(x)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3)
axes[0, 1].plot(x, y_sin)
axes[1, 2].plot(x, y_cos)
plt.show()
